   	  <h2>Monitor</h2>
        <p>The <em>monitor</em> is a back-end process able to capture relevant events from the <em>event bus</em> and process them (according to the definitions on an <em>ALIVE </em>organisational model) in order to generate new high level events, that are submitted to the <em>event bus</em>.</p>
<h3>Step Through</h3>
<h4>Configuration</h4>
        <p><em>Monitor</em> configuration can be specified via the <em>runtime dashboard.</em> There, users can specify the location of the <em>ALIVE organisational model</em> files to be used for processing and interpreting the events, in the case they want to run the <em>monitor</em> as a local back-end process. If the <em>monitor</em> is run a remote <em>back-end</em> process on a remote machine, users can specify the location of the remote <em>monitor.</em></p>
<h4>Running</h4>
        <p><em>Monitor</em> can be started via the <em>Start</em> <em>Monitor</em> button on the <em>runtime dashboard</em>. Notice that, having a back-end <em>monitor</em> process running is not mandatory for the ALIVE framework to work. Users are encouraged to start the <em>monitor</em> process only if they want their low level events to be processed, interpreted and submitted to the <em>event bus</em> as high level events. Thus, scenarios without the need for event interpretation (that is, <em>norms</em> and <em>counts-as</em> rules) are encouraged to avoid starting the <em>monitor</em> back-end process.</p>
